Thalasemia is a medical condition that causes the body to produce an abnormal form of hemoglobin. Hemoglobin is a protein in the red blood cells that carries oxygen and carbon dioxide. The genetic disorder can lead to a variety of symptoms that can vary in severity depending on the type of Thalasemia. Some of the common symptoms of Thalasemia include:
Fatigue and weakness
 Pale skin and shortness of breath
 Pain in the bones and joints
